Car Prices


Background

In math 325 class, we talked about price of Cadillacs analysis. The graph from the Cadillacs analysis shows that there are two different patterns in Devilles models. Question is why there two different patters?

Here is a mathematical model for the analysis. \[ \underbrace{Y_i}_{price} = \overbrace{\beta_0 + \beta_1 \underbrace{X_{i1}}_{mileage}}^{\text{DHS}} +\beta_2\underbrace{X_{i2}}_{\small \text{DTS}}+\beta_3\underbrace{X_{i3}}_{Sedan\ 4D} + \overbrace{\beta_4{X_{i1}}{X_{i2}}}^{\text{DTS interaction}} +\overbrace{\beta_5{X_{i1}}{X_{i3}}}^{\text{DHS interaction}} + \epsilon_i \]

Hypotheses \[ H_0: \beta_2 = 0, \quad H_0: \beta_3 = 0, \quad H_0: \beta_4 = 0, \quad H_0: \beta_5 = 0 \]

\[ H_a: \beta_2 \neq 0, \quad H_a:\beta_3 \neq 0, \quad H_a: \beta_4 \neq 0, \quad H_a: \beta_5 \neq 0 \]

Analysis

The graph below shows that Trim is the reason causing the two different patters.

ggplot(data = Car, aes(x = Mileage, y = Price)) + geom_point()  + aes(colour = Trim)  + stat_smooth(method = lm) + labs(title = "")

Running multiple regression test shows us price, mileage, and Trim has relation each other.

 car.lm <-lm(Price ~ Mileage + Trim +Mileage:Trim, data = Car)
pander(summary(car.lm))

These are five assumptions for multiple regression. Residuals VS Fitted indicates there is a linear regression and the variance of the error term is constant. QQPlot shows the error terms are normally distributed.You can also know the error rems are independent by Residuals VS Order plot.

par(mfrow=c(1,3))
plot(car.lm, which=1)
qqPlot(car.lm$residuals, id=FALSE)
plot(car.lm$residuals)

Interpretation

DHS Sedan lose price 43 cents per mile, DTS Sedan lose price 31 cents per mile, and Sedan lose 27 cents per mile. If you want to buy brand new car, DHS Sedan costs $46,151, DTS Sedan $44,420, and Sedan costs $38,019. The effect of price on mileage is significant and trim&mileage significantly impacts on price. Trim accounts for the distinct patterns.(check the p-value on summary table) Trim gives more extra insights on why Devilles is differ. P-value 0.08875 of DTS Sedan indicates that its not sufficient but we need to focus on that it DTS and DHS doesnt differ first but it does differ over times. Therefore, its hard to say its not sufficient.
